  "answer": "The critic’s case misreads the target’s mechanism and scope. The target does not claim the wanax was primarily a military leader; it claims his legitimacy required demonstrable divine favor through prosperity and victory—a condition the palatial redistributive and religious system was designed to manifest. The Linear B tablets’ portrayal of the wanax as a religious and redistributive figure is precisely the point: his ritual centrality was the means by which divine favor was secured and displayed. When that system failed to deliver material prosperity (drought, famine, military defeat), the ideological contract collapsed, delegitimizing the office itself. The disappearance of the wanax title with the palatial system is therefore consistent with an ideological crisis, not contradicted by it. The critic’s observation that post-palatial basileis retained ritual functions does not undermine the target, because the target’s scope explicitly excludes post-palatial continuity of ritual functions as a counterexample; the target addresses the disappearance of the wanax institution specifically, not the extinction of all ritual roles. The survival of lesser ritual figures (basileis) in a radically simplified political landscape is compatible with the collapse of the higher-order wanax ideology that depended on palatial-scale demonstration of divine favor."
